            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Anika Sharma\u2019s story is a carefully curated collection of choices, much like the exhibitions she manages. The only child of Indian immigrants who settled in Fresno, her upbringing was a blend of high academic expectations and a deeply ingrained work ethic. Her parents, a software engineer and a pharmacist, envisioned a secure future for her in medicine or law. However, a fifth-grade field trip to SFMOMA irrevocably altered that path. Standing before a massive Clyfford Still canvas, Anika didn't just see paint; she felt a narrative, a conversation she desperately wanted to join.\n\nThis quiet rebellion defined her educational journey. She pursued an art history undergraduate degree, a concession to her parents who saw it as a \"respectable\" humanities track, before making her definitive break: applying to the MFA in Curatorial Practice at the California College of the Arts. Moving to San Francisco was both a homecoming and a declaration of independence. The city\u2019s vibrant, chaotic energy was the perfect antidote to the structured predictability of her childhood.\n\nNow, as an Exhibitions Manager for a prominent SoMa gallery, Anika\u2019s life is a testament to organized passion. Her $82,000 salary demands careful budgeting in the city, but she finds luxury in her work. Her 4.8-mile commute on the MUNI from her rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Inner Richmond is a cherished ritual, a time for listening to art podcasts and sketching layout ideas in her notebook. Her days are a whirlwind of artist correspondence, logistical planning, and the satisfying, physical work of installation.\n\nHer social life is interwoven with her profession; friends are fellow curators, artists, and writers met through openings and late-night post-installation dinners. A serious relationship ended a year ago, a casualty of differing ambitions\u2014he wanted the suburbs, and she couldn't imagine leaving the epicenter of her world. Anika\u2019s dream is to one day curate a major exhibition at the de Young Museum, focusing on emerging South Asian diaspora artists. For her, San Francisco isn't just a place to live; it's the canvas, the medium, and the subject of a life she is intentionally and beautifully composing."
        },
